<subSubSection id="B7F837479F4C33B4474A4F1CC771DCFE" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="69DB266D52700DA1145625B10C869247" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">
The differences from the subspecies 
<taxonomicName id="1AA004DE45D6F40EA372AED6288B05F3" class="Arachnida" family="Camisiidae" genus="Heminothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="capillatus" subSpecies="septentrionalis">septentrionalis Sellnick</taxonomicName>
in Hammer, 1944 (recently redescribed by Sellnick &amp; Forsslund, 1955, p. 519, figs. 21-22) are of minor importance. The species has faint dorsal ridges in the anterior part of the notogaster, which appear to be absent in the subspecies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
